{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_foxglove_ver01/data/sn84024221/00340580084/1946040801/0930.xml":{"full_text":"FAIR\n'FEARLESS\nONE OF\nENROLLMENT IN NEGRO\nSCHOOLS REACH PEAK YEAR\nWASHINGTON, Apr. 8 (ANP)\n\u2014A peak enrollment in Negro col\nleges and universities throughout\nthe country has been reached, ac\ncording to a recent survey conduct\ned by Dr. Martin D. Jenkins, a rep\nresentative of Howard university\u2019s\ndepartment of education.\nOne hundred eight institutions\nreport a total of 43,868 resident\ncollege student during the fall term\nof the current school year, includ\ning 41,741 undergraduates, the\nsurvey revealed, which is an in\ncrease of 16 per cent over the same\nterm of last year. Almost all insti\ntutions reported a gain in enroll\nment over last year, Dr. Jenkins\nsaid.\nAlthough some gain in male un\ndergraduates is reported, male stu\ndents constitute only 22 per cent\nof the total, whereas in pre-war\nyears they were about 45 per cent\nof the total enrollment. Private\ninstitutions represent 54 per cent\nof the total enrollment, of which 62\nper cent are in fully accredited in\nstitutions.\nThe report, published in the\nspring issue of the Journal of Ne\ngro BJducation published by the\nbureau of educational research of\nHoward university, reveals that\nHoward is the largest institution\nreporting an enrollment of 3,087\nstudents during the fall term of\n1945, and 4,780 students during\nthe school year of 1944-1945. Full\nemployment will result in expand\ning enrollment, Dr. Jenkins said.\nWidespread unemployment will in\nevitably bring a decline in the num\nber of youth attending institutions\nof higher education. A typical in\nstitution has an enrollment of only\n310 students, the survey reported.\nAn appreciable number of dis\ncharged war veterans are return\ning to colleges for further educa\ntion, Dr. Jenkinssaid. Eighty-seven\ninstitutions report a total of 1,310\nveterans of college level and 663\nof below college level enrolled un\nder the vocational rehabilitation or\nGI Bill of Rights, as of Nov, 1,\n1945.\nEnrollment in graduate and pro\nfessional curricula totaled 2,127\nstudents during the fall term of\n1945, and 3,907 students during\nthe full school year of 1944 and\n1945.\nB.THE\nIt is doubtful if this country has\nknown a tragedy more depressing\nthan the Negro\u2019s disillusionment at\nthe conclusion of World War I. The\nNegro soldiers fought valiantly\nagainst dreadful odds to save, as\nthey thought, the world for de\nmocracy. When the war was over\neven more violent pressure was ex\nerted on Negroes throughout the\nUnited States. It seemed at times\nthat even the little that he had\nwould be taken away.\nThe cessation and immigration\nsaved what looked like a fateful sit\nuation in that it left labor short\nages which Negroes were called\nupon to fill at the north. Of course\nthis alleviation came by the way of\nfortuitous circumstances** father\nthan by any geunine relinquish\nment of white America of its color\nbarriers. Negroes were forced to\ndrink from the bitter cup of disil\nlusionment and bitter indeed was\nthe hellish draught.\nBaffled in his legitimate aspira\ntions to share the democracy for\nwhich thousands of his race men\ndied, distraught at the increased\npressure applied by the white-su\npremacists to preserve inviolate\nthe status quo, the Negro gallant\nly girded himself to the awkward\ntask of trying to fight hisjway out\nof the morass of moral calamity\nthat had overtaken him. Then came\nWorld War II.\nHe entered World War II dis\nillusioned but hopeful that some\nhow he as one of the step-citizens\nof the nation might profit by the\nsuffering which he shared in full\nmeasure. He went a little higher in\nthe counsels of the nation but\nwhether it was to fall a little lower\nin the period of Disillusionment II\nremains to be seen.\nIf as Churchill has alleged Rus\nsia has thrown a curtain of iron\nsecrecy about most of eastern Eu\nrope, America has thrown about\nthe cause of race relations an iron\ncurtain of intimidation and laissez\nfaire that is disheartening to ser\nious minded interracialists\nthroughout the nation. If inter\nracialism cannot help in this cruel\nperiod of the Negro\u2019s disillusion\nment II, then we may as well close\nshop!\nCombined With OHIO EXPRESS\nTHE TWO ONLT NEGRO DAILIES IN TH\nIt has come about that the Ne\u00ad\nDAILY\nVol. 5\u2014No. 13 DAYTON, OHIO, MONDAY, APRIL 8, 1946 Price 3c\nAttorney Dickerson Protest Exclusion Of Negro\nLawyers To Probe Army Courts Martial Trail\nDoon Gordon B.\n(JLLETIN\ngro veterans are being rebuffed on\nevery side. The doors of job op\nportunities are being slammed in\nthe faces of our brave sons who\nhave a just right to expect better\nthings of their country. Many of\nthe skills the veterans acquired\nmust be junked if these young men\nare to earn their daily bread. Un\nfortunately, the federal govern\nment which opened opportunities\nto these higher skills is not in posi\ntion to compel private industry to\npurchase these skills and so the Ne\ngro veterans are left suspended be\ntween the things they want to do\nand the things they have to do to\nearn their daily bread. The failure\nof the FEPC cause made such eco\nnomic doom inevitable. It all\namounts to a great Disillusionment\nIn some cases which have come\nto our attention the returned vet\nerans are refusing to cast aside\ntheir finer skills to return to their\nformer economic niches in the com\nmunity. They are determining to\nsit it out. But there is grave doubt\nthat by siting down they can break\ndown the iron curtain^ Jiostile\nforces have raised. It would be ex\nceedingly unfortunate if a veteran\nwere so determined to get some\nthing better than he left something\ngood pass on to other hands.\nHowever it may hurt cur pride\nto admit it, in the last analysis sur\nvival a matter of what we must\ndo as well as what we want to do.\nOur wants are one thing but grim\nnecessity may not take cognizance\nthereof. Just how to break down\nthe iron curtain of economic dis\ncrimination is the pressing ques\ntion before the Negro in particu\nlar and the nation in general.\nIt all goes back to the old doc\ntrine of the Double-Duty Dollar so\nlong enunciated in this column. To\nday the best jobs of Negroes are\nprovided by the employment of the\nDouble-Duty Dollar. If these young\nreturning veterans are to be res\ncued from their tragic plight, it\nmust be largely through the prom\nulgation of the gospel of the Dou\nble-Duty Dollar until the race is\neconomically converted. Some of\nour \u201cscholars\u2019* have gainsaid the\ndoctrine but they have not to date\nbroughtforth anything better\nCONSTRUCTIVE\nPROGRESSIVE\nE WORLD\nCHICAGO, Apr. 8 (ANP)\u2014Ex\nclusion to Negro lawyers to probe\ncourt-martial injustices was pro\ntested here by Atty. Earl B. Dick\nerson, president of the National\nBar association, in a letter to Secy,\nof War Patterson. Members of the\nAmerican Bar association have\nbeen invited by the war depart\nment to inquire into army courts\nmartial procedures.\n\u201cI submit that this is a tragic\nmistake,\u201d Dickerson\u2019s letter said.\n\u201cThe American Bar association\ndoes not admit qualified Negro\nlawyers to membership. Thus, the\norganization you have selected to\ninquire impartially into a matter\nof vital importance to all Ameri\ncans, is by its very organization\ncompletely unfitted for the im\nportant task assigned to it.\u201d\nDickerson pointed out that, ac\ncording to war department fig,\nures, 17 percent of all American\nsoldiers convicted of military of\nfenses during this war were Ne\ngroes. \u201cTherefore, a segregated\ngroup that has never exceeded 9^2\nper cent of the total strength of the\narmy contributed this dispropor\ntionate percentage to the number\nof recorded offenses. Obviously,\none of the most important consid\nerations before any investigative\nboard inquiring into army justice\nis whether or not soldiers who\nstand accused of offenses receive\nfair and impartial trials.\n\u201cThere is no likelihood that this\nwill be inquired into by a group ap\npointed by the American Bar asso\nciation,\u201d the NBA president said.\nImportant notice to vets who\nwish to enter school: Do not regis\nter for entry into a school until you\nhave first secured your \u201cletter of\nentitlement\u201d from and have cleared\nthrough an office of Veterans ad\nministration. Failure to do this will\nresult in a delay in getting your\nmonthly subsistence checks. Do not\nfail to do this.\nGen. Bradley has promised the\nUFWA that a new department, the\ndivision of personnel relations, will\nbe created to handle all employe\nproblems in Veterans administra\ntion. The new division will operate\nas a separate function apart from\nthe personnel office, concerning it\nself solely with with the individual\nproblems of the employes.","height":"19497","width":"13071"}}
